Deployments


Very common in industry.

Deployment Strategies
Deploying new versions carefully is important to avoid downtime.

1. Blue-Green Deployment
Concept
Maintain two identical environments:
Blue → current live version
Green → new version
Traffic initially goes to Blue.
Deploy new version to Green.
Once verified:
Switch traffic to Green.

Example
Version 1 running for users.
Version 2 deployed separately.
When stable:
Users moved to Version 2 instantly.
Zero downtime.

Benefit
Easy rollback.
If issue:
Switch back to Blue.

2. Canary Deployment
Concept
New version gradually released to small percentage of users first.
Example:
5% users → new version
If stable:
20%
50%
100%

Example
Instagram releases new feature to limited users first.
If bugs found:
Stop rollout.

Benefit
Reduced risk.

3. Rolling Deployment
Concept
Servers updated gradually one by one.
Not all at once.

Example
10 application instances running.
Update:
Instance 1
Then 2
Then 3
Until all updated.
Old and new versions coexist temporarily.

Benefit
No downtime.

Real World Example of CI/CD Flow
Developer pushes code to GitHub.
GitHub Actions pipeline starts:


Code builds


Tests run


Docker image created


Deploy to Kubernetes


Rolling deployment updates production


Entire process automated.
That is CI/CD in action.

Easy Analogy
Suppose factory making cars.
Without CI/CD:
Manual assembly and inspection.
Slow.

With CI/CD:
Automated assembly line.
Fast, reliable, scalable.

